This sample was collected at Playa Guiones, the beach nearest a small town in the Guanacaste region of Costa Rica. The beach faces open ocean and is part of a national refuge. It is a beach break frequented by surfers year-round but is never very populous. During the week that I sampled, there were two rather large swells coming in. Over the years that I have surfed there, I would consider this to be one of the cleanest beaches I have seen, but this could be due to the strong local recycling program and strong local support of environmental conservation and sustainability. Please let me know if I can provide any further information.

This sample was taken at Playa Ostional, Costa Rica, which is part of a national refuge. This beach is relatively close to the other beach (Playa Guiones) from which I took a sample, but it is far less frequented by humans because of sea turtle nesting conservation. In fact, up until a couple of years ago, there were no bridges to get there during the rainy season, so the very small village and turtles remain very isolated for part of the year. There are two rivers at either end of the beach, but they don't flow into the ocean during dry season, which doesn't end until April or May. Please let me know if I can provide further information.

column16: Former Mining Area

How the Sample was taken: The boat has a retractable swim platform on the stern.  I lay down on this swim platform and put the empty bottle into the ocean with my bare arm and hand.  The boat was going about six knots.  I rinsed the bottle with ocean water twice before filling it.  Potential microplastics contributed to the sample by the sampling process: The boat received a fresh coat of bottom paint about 12 days ago.  It is a very dark blue color.  It may be that the water flowing over the hull broke free some particles of paint.

How the sample was taken, and potential microplastics introduced during the testing process were the same as sample one, but of course the elapsed time since the bottom paint has increased.  	The sample was taken when we thought we were in the Humbolt Current that runs up the S American West Coast from Patagonia, and then turns West in the vicinity of the Equator.  We had noticed that the water temperature had dropped over a couple of days from 31.6 to 27.2 degrees C when the sample was taken.  Also our GPS calculated Speed Over Ground had increased a couple of knots, suggesting a favorable current.
I didn't get the water temp.  If need be, use the average between sample 2 and 4.
Because it was dark, I was wearing a safety harness made of red and yellow nylon.  I was always wearing a pair of swim trunks.  One pair is dark gray, the other is green.
Collected off swim platform at 7 knots under sail.  Wore green swim trunks.
Collected off swim platform at 7 knots under motor sailing.  Wore green swim trunks.

Collected off swim platform at 7 knots under motor sailing.  Wore gray swim trunks. This was the last sample - I felt that I could carry no more than 7 liters in my luggage.  A couple of general notes:  1) The trip was called Panama to Hawaii, but it was really Panama to Tahiti.  The boat I originally planned to join didn't pan out and this one did.  2) I did not record the time normally because it is not included on your data collection sheet.  I put 12:00 on your web form when I did not know the time.

column9: King George Island in Antarctica. South Shetland Islands
column16: Taken from the rocky beach boat landing zone in from of the Russian and Chilean research stations. Commonly used landing zone for water crafts. A very developed area for Antarctica with a lot of large machinery buildings and various operations just on shore from where the sample was taken. Was warm with a lot of snow melt flowing into bay where sample was taken

Another remote location. Very small patch of land and mostly glacier. Small rocky shoreline. Penguins in the area. Sample was taken right next to zodiac boats. Rushed having to leave land early due to high winds and ice flows entering the area that could block return to expedition ship.

Rocky beach next to relatively large land mass or hill with a lot of penguin activity. Glaciers and snow everywhere. Zodiac boats in the area but sample taken upcurrent. Initially messed up sample taking it wearing synthetic gloves while a friend was getting a picture from shore but retook sample after rerinsing bottle and following procedure.

Rocky beach on Half Mood Island. Lots of penguins and penguin feces around the beach. Some old uninhabited research and outpost buildings in the area but away from beach sample was taken. Normally unused beach but used that day as small watercraft zodiacs landing for the race. Sample taken up current from where zodiacs were operating going back to ship.
1ft offshore, fun small swell. yewww

2 ft peelers, it's my secret spot, but you're welcome anytime. plug the coordinates in to a gps. a bit of a walk, but worth it

column16: Diego Suarez lies within a massive natural harbour with narrow constricted entrance. No opportunity to take a sample as we came into the harbour and the best I could do was a sample off the back of the ship moored at the dock. Water looked a bit murky but relatively clean with some floating algae and big Long Tom fish about one meter in length cruised by as I took the sample
